The goods arrived!

So what I had not told you yet is that my expensive rare greenhouse lights and fans didnt come on during my departure for ten days!

I had filled all of the trays with water and as there was limited light, no heat and no air flow the water turned stagnent and mould started to kick in! 

I cant begin to explain the smell of every single pot! I had to wait 24 hours to get my substrate mix order in too so you can imagine how anxious I was as I knowingly left my plants to rot another night.

I have lost a few and have saved most but again lost a lot of growth. Every cloud has a silver lining, I remembered to film bits of my soil mix so here you go! 

Compost - seaweed based
Perlite
Vermiculite
Horticultural charcoal
Sphagnum moss
Fine orchid pine bark
Chunky coco husk pieces
Worm castings

This is just my mix at the moment, and they tend to adapt over time as well as depend on what I have hanging around however this is a complete full fat mix for aroids!

Ive now got to attack greenhouse number two! Wish me luck! Peace & love tiny phone people! わ答

Work in progress. 

Found this piece of wood on the beach among other parts from a boat that met its fate in the ocean somehow. 

I make certain it is a stable..not too far gone and thick enough piece of upcycled wood before I even consider it to be used as mosaic substrate. I love it rough around the edges but the body of it needs to be intact and strong for me to slap some glass on it or I will not use it. 

No, this will not be used as a mosaic floor. 
No, this will not be hung outdoors. 
No, this will not be hung anywhere there is high humidity..like a bathroom. 

Yes you should always listen to your instructors when they are advising their techniques they teach and what substrate to use for a particular technique and purpose. Always. 

I began using found wood in moments for my substrate and learning what I could properly use on wood out of necessity when I wasnt able to afford buying other substrates. I also loved the idea that I could find a way to take something tossed or forgotten and give it a new life as art. I love the contrast of reflective glass against weathered wood a lot. So this is how I began experimenting with how to make something that would in fact outlive us all and have the ability to keep doing something I just absolutely loved doing. 
I just wanted to keep making art and in doing I am practicing and learning and getting my ideas out there. Whether it be a cave wall or a scrap of wood from a boat found on a beachI am doing what millions of artists before me did. Finding a way to create and express myself.

This week, Audrey and I had the absolute pleasure of touring @rufflefarm in St Peters! The brains behind the operation are Jess and Joel - Inner Westies who, just like us, wanted to farm in the urban setting! Well, they've definitely achieved this, growing over 70kgs of culinary mushrooms a week which they supply to restaurants and the public!

Their enthusiasm for mushrooms was infectious! It felt great connecting with them and 'growing the mycelial network' in Sydney.

They have a huge variety of mushrooms on offer from golden enokis, to lions mane, to chestnuts, and many types of oysters.

*** GARDENERS ***
They need to find a home for 300kgs of this perfectly great compostable material each and every week - so - Permaculture at the Pubbers and @sydneyediblegardentrail hosts and visitors - this is a great opportunity to connect with them and pick up some great (and free) material for your compost pile!

They are located at 21 Caroline Lane, St Peters - the bins are just sitting outside the garage door. No need to knock, and you can take as much as you like ぉ

Need a reminder?! HYPERroots is the ONLY growing medium certified as compostable by BPI, which is a third-party verification of ASTM standards in North America. But what's the difference between biodegradable and compostable? Biodegradable means it can be broken down by microorganisms and turns into natural substances. There are fewer standards for testing and verification for biodegradability. On the other hand, compostable products break down into nutrient-rich humus, also known as compost. There are multiple criterion for compostability but it typically requires 90% biodegradation within 6 months and disintegration within 12 weeks. All compostable products are biodegradable, but not all biodegradable products are compostable, meaning HYPERroots has passed the benchmarks to be certified as compostable伙!
